---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---
<BaseLayout title="Ministry Turbulence Index" description="The IMWA's classification system for multi-variable ministry crisis events. Four variables. Five categories. One rarest designation: the four-variable confluence event.">
  <article class="page">
    <div class="doc-header">
      <div class="doc-classification">IMWA TECHNICAL PUBLICATION · MTI-2026-001</div>
      <h1>The Ministry Turbulence Index</h1>
      <div class="doc-subtitle">A Classification Framework for Multi-Variable Ministry Crisis Events</div>
      <div class="doc-meta">
        <span>Prepared by: IMWA Emergency Response Desk</span>
        <span>Subcommittee on Watching MinistryWatch Watch Things</span>
        <span>Activation Threshold: Two or more variables simultaneously present</span>
        <span>Last Triggered: Barnabas Aid, June 2026</span>
      </div>
    </div>

    <section>
      <h2>Overview</h2>
      <p>The Ministry Turbulence Index (MTI) is the IMWA's classification system for assessing the severity of ministry crisis events based on the number of concurrent destabilizing variables present. Unlike single-metric accountability scores, the MTI recognizes that ministry turbulence is rarely the product of one factor — it is almost always the product of several factors arriving simultaneously, in the manner of unwelcome houseguests who have somehow coordinated their schedules.</p>
      <p>The MTI operates on a five-tier classification. Each tier corresponds to a specific number of concurrently active variables. The rarest and most alarming designation is the <strong>four-variable confluence event</strong>, which the IMWA has documented only seven times in its operating history, most recently in the Barnabas Aid case of June 2026.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>The Four Foundational Variables</h2>
      <p>The MTI tracks four primary destabilizing variables. Any combination of these variables, present simultaneously, triggers a corresponding MTI classification:</p>

      <table class="data-table">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Variable</th>
            <th>Description</th>
            <th>Indicator Phrases in Coverage</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>V1 — Founder Event</strong></td>
            <td>Death, incapacitation, departure, or formal removal of a founding figure</td>
            <td>"founder," "passed away," "stepped down," "amid questions"</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>V2 — Whistleblower Activation</strong></td>
            <td>Emergence of internal sources alleging misconduct, financial irregularity, or governance failure</td>
            <td>"sources allege," "former employee," "complaint filed," "whistleblower"</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>V3 — Financial Opacity Event</strong></td>
            <td>Missing, unexplained, or contested funds; audit failures; unexplained balance sheet movements</td>
            <td>"missing funds," "unaccounted," "audit," "financial irregularity"</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>V4 — Regulatory Intervention</strong></td>
            <td>Action by a government oversight body, charity commission, or legal authority</td>
            <td>"interim managers," "appointed by," "regulatory," "court-ordered"</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>MTI Classification Tiers</h2>

      <table class="data-table tier-table">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>MTI Tier</th>
            <th>Variables Present</th>
            <th>Classification Name</th>
            <th>IMWA Response Level</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr class="tier-1">
            <td><strong>MTI-1</strong></td>
            <td>1 of 4</td>
            <td>Routine Disturbance</td>
            <td>Standard monitoring. Staff are notified. Lunch proceeds.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="tier-2">
            <td><strong>MTI-2</strong></td>
            <td>2 of 4</td>
            <td>Elevated Concern</td>
            <td>Enhanced monitoring. A subcommittee is formed. Lunch is shortened.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="tier-3">
            <td><strong>MTI-3</strong></td>
            <td>3 of 4</td>
            <td>Significant Event</td>
            <td>Full institutional mobilization. The subcommittee meets twice. Lunch is a working lunch.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="tier-4">
            <td><strong>MTI-4</strong></td>
            <td>4 of 4</td>
            <td>Four-Variable Confluence Event</td>
            <td>Emergency session convened. Standing appointments canceled. Lunch does not occur.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="tier-5 row-terminus">
            <td><strong>MTI-4+</strong></td>
            <td>4 of 4 + cascading secondary variables</td>
            <td>Cascading Confluence Event</td>
            <td><strong>All-hands. Press release drafted. Someone calls legal. Lunch is forgotten entirely.</strong></td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>The Barnabas Aid Event (June 2026): A Case Study</h2>
      <p>The Barnabas Aid situation reported by MinistryWatch in June 2026 represents the most recent confirmed MTI-4 designation in the IMWA's active files. The four variables were present as follows:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>V1 (Founder Event):</strong> Death of the organization's founder ✓</li>
        <li><strong>V2 (Whistleblower Activation):</strong> Whistleblower complaints surfaced ✓</li>
        <li><strong>V3 (Financial Opacity Event):</strong> Allegations of missing funds ✓</li>
        <li><strong>V4 (Regulatory Intervention):</strong> UK Charity Commission appointment of interim managers ✓</li>
      </ul>
      <p>All four variables confirmed. MTI-4 designation applied. Emergency session convened. MinistryWatch's coverage was assessed by the IMWA's Tone Calibration Division as competent but insufficiently alarmed — a Urgency Conveyance Scale score of 3 out of 10. The IMWA filed a formal notation. The notation is seven pages. The salutation took three of them.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Historical MTI-4 Events</h2>
      <table class="data-table">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>#</th>
            <th>Institution</th>
            <th>Year</th>
            <th>V1</th>
            <th>V2</th>
            <th>V3</th>
            <th>V4</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>1–6</td><td colspan="6" style="font-style:italic; color: var(--color-text-muted);">Classified. Available upon written request to the IMWA's Archive of Consequential Events, subject to a 90-day review period and the Committee on Disclosures approving the request, which it has not yet done for any request submitted since the committee's formation in 2019.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>7</td><td>Barnabas Aid</td><td>2026</td><td>✓</td><td>✓</td><td>✓</td><td>✓</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </section>

    <section class="signature-block">
      <p>Published by the <strong>IMWA Emergency Response Desk</strong><br />Subcommittee on Watching MinistryWatch Watch Things<br /><em>Institute for Ministry Watch Accountability</em></p>
      <p class="sig-disclaimer">The Ministry Turbulence Index is a classification tool, not a prediction instrument. The IMWA does not predict ministry crises. The IMWA classifies them after they have occurred, which is different, and which does not make the IMWA responsible for any of them.</p>
      <p class="sig-back">← <a href="/posts/007-ministrywatch-calmly-reports-on-complete-collapse-of-civiliz">Return to the Barnabas Aid assessment</a> · <a href="/imwa/urgency-conveyance-scale">View the Urgency Conveyance Scale</a></p>
    </section>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .page { max-width: 760px; }
  .doc-header { border: 2px solid var(--color-navy); padding: 1.5rem; margin-bottom: 2rem; background: var(--color-bg-alt); text-align: center; }
  .doc-classification { font-size: 0.6rem; letter-spacing: 0.18em; text-transform: uppercase; font-weight: 700; color: var(--color-gold); background: var(--color-navy); padding: 0.25rem 0.75rem; display: inline-block; margin-bottom: 1rem; }
  h1 { font-size: clamp(1.4rem, 3vw, 2rem); margin-bottom: 0.5rem; }
  .doc-subtitle { font-style: italic; color: var(--color-text-muted); font-size: 1rem; margin-bottom: 1rem; }
  .doc-meta { display: flex; flex-wrap: wrap; justify-content: center; gap: 0.25rem 1.5rem; font-size: 0.75rem; color: var(--color-text-muted); border-top: 1px solid var(--color-border); padding-top: 0.75rem; margin-top: 0.75rem; }
  section { margin-bottom: 2.5rem; }
  h2 { font-size: 1rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; padding-bottom: 0.4rem; border-bottom: 2px solid var(--color-navy); text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.06em; font-family: var(--font-sans); font-weight: 700; }
  p, li { line-height: 1.75; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-size: 0.95rem; }
  ul { padding-left: 1.5rem; }
  .data-table { width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 0.82rem; margin: 0.75rem 0; }
  .data-table th { background: var(--color-navy); color: white; font-family: var(--font-sans); font-weight: 700; font-size: 0.7rem; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.06em; padding: 0.6rem 0.75rem; text-align: left; vertical-align: bottom; }
  .th-sub { display: block; font-weight: 400; opacity: 0.75; font-size: 0.65rem; margin-top: 0.15rem; }
  .data-table td { border: 1px solid var(--color-border); padding: 0.5rem 0.75rem; vertical-align: top; }
  .data-table tr:nth-child(even) td { background: var(--color-bg-alt); }
  .tier-1 td { border-left: 4px solid #27ae60; }
  .tier-2 td { border-left: 4px solid #f39c12; }
  .tier-3 td { border-left: 4px solid #e67e22; }
  .tier-4 td { border-left: 4px solid #c0392b; }
  .tier-5 td { border-left: 4px solid #7d0000; }
  .row-terminus td { background: #fff3f3 !important; font-weight: 600; border-top: 2px solid #c0392b; }
  .signature-block { border-top: 2px solid var(--color-navy); padding-top: 1.5rem; font-size: 0.88rem; }
  .signature-block p { margin-bottom: 1rem; }
  .sig-disclaimer { font-size: 0.78rem; font-style: italic; color: var(--color-text-muted); border-top: 1px solid var(--color-border); padding-top: 0.75rem; }
  .sig-back { font-size: 0.8rem; margin-top: 1.5rem; }
  .sig-back a { color: var(--color-navy); }
</style>
